default2) The proposal that providers of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies should only be paid for work done on the case if the Court defaultgrants permission for the application to proceeddefault&#xa0;
defaultThis proposal both as originally put and as now amended is very complex in its implications. 
defaultThe complexity itself i
defaults an obstacle to efficient litig
defaultation and fairness. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOur understanding from legal practit
defaultioners is that very often it is the pre-action steps in ju
defaultdicial 
defaultreview which are effective, in that the Home Office will often then concede the case, 
defaultor 
defaultretract the decision.
default 
defaultThese pre-action steps will still be legally aidable, but part of what makes the
defaultm effective is the anticipation that judicial review proceedings will follow if no settlement is achieved. 
defaultWhat the proposed changes will do is heighten the risk for practitioners of issuing judicial review proceedings, no doubt increasing their caution in
default issuing proceedings. 
defaultThe chances of success in a public law action are hard to predict, and there is scope for more than one reputable view of the likely outcome of an application. The proposal introduces a costs mechanism which will infl
defaultuence the conduct
default of
default litigation 
defaultin a situation where the applicant has no alternative remedy 
defaultto protect life and limb. 
defaultAs set out above, a
default person subjected to a government mistake, abuse or omission
default cannot choose some alternative path such as mediation, as suggested in the
default consultation document. Public law matters are not susceptible to these alternatives. 
default&#xa0;
defaultFigures for the outcome o
defaultf judicial review applications 
defaultdo not factor in 
defaultthose cases where 
defaultthe less expensive 
defaultpre-action steps
default, backed up by the real threat of judicial review, 
defaulthave
default succeeded
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe suggest that the most effective and just way to reduce public spending on legal aid on asylum and immigration matters is to improve the quality of Home Office handling of applications, 
defaultthereby re
defaultducing the need for court time or pre-action steps.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are aware of the very tight constraints on legal aid firms locally who do immigration and asylum work. 
defaultIt is already 
defaultoften 
defaultdifficult to find a representative who 
defaultcan act quickly and effectively. 
defaultWe
default would be very concerned if solicitors
default were made to should
defaulter the costs of preparing an application for
default judicial review. Our fear is that asylum seekers and refugees would find it extremely difficult to get any represent
defaultat
defaultion
default in what are sometimes the most critical situations 
default(e.g. when f
defaultaced with detention or removal).
default&#xa0;
defaultThe proposal 
defaultmight encourage a kind of brinkmanship in the government side, and settling the case (i.e. withdrawing a possibly life-threatening decision su
defaultch as to remove someone from the UK) 
defaultmay become less a matter of finding an effective way to see justice done, and more
default a
default 
defaultgambl
defaulte
default on the applicant’s solicitor being unwilling to bear the risk of 
default(further) 
defaultcosts by going to court. 
defaultIt is obvious that this is 
defaultnot a way to ensu
defaultre justice or access to a court, especially where people are vulnerable to 
defaultlife-threatening effects of 
defaultstate action. 
