default&#xa0;
default3)The proposal that legal aid should be removed for all cases assessed as having “borderline” prospects of success.default&#xa0;
defaultTh
defaultis proposal ignores the unpredictable nature of public law and the very high stakes for the client. 
defaultAs with the previous points, these proposals miss the 
defaultissues that are at stake in asylum cases. 
defaultIt c
defaultannot be right 
defaultfor the UK
default, as a signatory to the R
defaultefugee Convention, 
defaultto deny a hearing 
defaultwhere 
defaultan asylum seeker’s challenge to removal or t
defaulthe refusal of their claim is
default slightly more likely to succeed than fail.
default The standard of proof in refugee cases is ‘a reasonable degree of likelihood’ that the feared ris
defaultk will materialise. As Sedley LJ said
default, 
defaultcomparing the refugee claim to a faulty type of car, even if only one car in ten actually crashes, most people would think there was a real risk of travelling
default in such a car. I
defaultf they had a choice they would
default not do it.
default When the risk is of death or serious injury, a borderline case is one that must be heard. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn our experience, 
defaultasylum 
defaultcases assessed as borderline may be those where successive errors and omissions have eroded and obscured the merits of the case
default, but wher
defaulte significant issues remain to be properly determined. An assessment as borderline may be
default the wisest course for a legal aid practitioner who is not able to really delve into the history of the matter or test out perhaps contentious legal points until they have the funding to do so. 
defaultWhere the law is unclear, disputed or needs to be tested, a le
defaultgal aid practitioner may not in conscience be able to assess the merits as more than borderline, but it is precisely these cases which need the protection of publicly funded advice and representation.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are very concerned that the people who have alread
defaulty had the worst experience of justice and fairness within the system will, if this rule is imposed, be the very ones who will suffer again and be effectively excluded from protection. Again we would stress, asylum cases are often about life and death issue
defaults. Access to a court is not a luxury. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe strength of the case is only one dimension of assessing its importance and whether the public purse should fund it. 
defaultThe importance of the matter at stake should also be a criterion, and where breaches of fundamen
defaulttal rights are in issue, as they are in asylum
default cases, 
defaultthe threshold 
defaultshould be a low one. This is to protect the individual and 
defaultto 
defaultoffer scrutiny to 
defaultprotect 
defaultthe public authority 
defaultfrom a
default breach 
defaultof 
defaultits international obligations.
